    'RIVER_S08_TRADE_001' => [
        'briefing_json' => [
            'en' => [
                'situation'           => 'You are Master of a 135m x 17m inland motor vessel, a standard large Rhine vessel, currently at Rotterdam preparing to load steel products for delivery to Basel — the full Rhine transit from the Dutch coast to Switzerland. Water levels on the Rhine are critically low: the Kaub gauge reads 78 cm (normal for this time of year is approximately 250 cm), and the Pegel Ruhrort reads 215 cm. The Kaub gauge is the critical reference for the Middle Rhine between Mainz and Koblenz, where the river narrows and the channel depth is most restricted. At a Kaub gauge reading of 78 cm, the effective navigable channel depth is approximately 1.9 metres. Your vessel\'s light draft (empty) is 0.8 metres. Based on your vessel\'s hydrostatic tables, the maximum safe cargo load at this water level — allowing for the mandatory minimum under-keel clearance of 20 cm at Kaub — gives you a maximum operational draft of approximately 1.7 metres, which corresponds to roughly 1,200 tonnes of cargo (versus the vessel\'s normal full-load capacity of 3,500 tonnes at full draft of 3.5 metres). The cargo offered is 2,800 tonnes of steel coils — significantly more than you can carry in a single trip. The shipper proposes three options: (a) Load 1,200 tonnes now, deliver to Basel, return for the remaining 1,600 tonnes — a double trip that would take approximately 14 days total and incur an additional €85,000 in fuel, transit fees, and operational costs; (b) Load 1,200 tonnes on your vessel, the shipper sends the remaining 1,600 tonnes by rail — but the shipper wants a €30,000 freight reduction from your contracted rate because they are bearing the additional rail transport cost; (c) Wait in Rotterdam for water levels to recover — the meteorological forecast suggests 5 to 7 days before the Kaub gauge might reach 150 cm (which would allow a load of approximately 2,200 tonnes at a draft of approximately 2.8 metres), but there is no guarantee, and forecasts during low water periods are notoriously unreliable. Your vessel costs €3,500 per day in fixed costs (crew wages, insurance, vessel financing, maintenance provisions) regardless of whether it is moving or waiting at berth. Three other vessels from competing operators are known to be negotiating for the same cargo — if you do not accept the shipment, another operator will take it. You know from long experience that low water surcharges (Kleinwasserzuschlag) are in effect: the freight rate for Rotterdam-Basel is currently at 180% of the normal rate due to the low water conditions, making every tonne carried highly profitable. However, the consequences of loading too deep and grounding at Kaub are severe: obstruction of the waterway (the narrow channel means all traffic stops), potential hull damage, waterway authority fines (up to €50,000), insurance complications, and reputational damage. The Kaub passage operates a "traffic light" system managed by the waterway authority (WSA) — vessels are required to declare their draft, and those exceeding the published maximum permissible draft are prohibited from transiting.',
